07018nam a22007335i 9780773585744DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735857447 a10.1515/97807735857442doi  a(DE-B1597)655346  a(OCoLC)806255211  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJC328.6bE54 2011eb 7aPOL0080002bisacsh04a303.6/21 aGillies, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aElections in Dangerous Places :bDemocracy and the Paradoxes of Peacebuilding /cDavid Gillies. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tElectoral Democracy and the Paradoxes of Peacebuilding -- tElections in Conflict Situations: An Overview -- tUnderstanding Elections in Conflict Situations -- tLessons Learned From Country Situations -- tElections and the Future of Afghanistan -- tIraq’s Conflicted Transition to Democracy: Analyzing Elections in a Violent Society -- tDemocracy in Africa: Rumours of Its Demise Have Been Greatly Exaggerated -- tElections, Governance, and Secession in Sudan -- tElection-Related Conflict Resolution Mechanisms: The 2006 Elections in the Democratic Republic of the Congo -- tDying to Win: Elections, Political Violence, and Institutional Decay in Kenya* -- tLessons Learned and Forgotten: The International Community and Electoral Conflict Management in Kenya* -- tPolicy and Practice in Electoral Conflict Management -- tMerging Conflict Management with Electoral Practice: The IFES Experience -- tPreventing and Mitigating Election-Related Conflict and Violence: The Role of Electoral Justice -- tElectoral Dispute Resolution: A Personal Perspective -- tCanada’s Role in International Democracy Promotion -- tIs Democracy Promotion “Globaloney” or a Categorical Imperative?* -- tOngoing Dilemmas of Democratization: Canada and Afghanistan -- tAn Ounce of Prevention: Preliminary Implications for Policy and Practice -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough a series of frank and incisive case studies of conflicted countries, contributors' chapters challenge the centrality and timing of elections as a key pillar of reconstruction at a war's end. They underline the dangers in rushing elections, compromising principles, and lowering the bar for what constitutes free and fair elections in situations of conflict. The authors also underline the economic cost of elections in uncertain political situations and argue that global taxpayers, who must bear the burden, are justified in questioning the value of ill-timed elections. A candid and important study of political turmoil, Elections in Dangerous Places provides valuable lessons and practical advice on how to better mitigate conflict and violence before, during, and after highly charged elections. Contributors include Thomas S. Axworthy (Walter and Duncan Gordon Foundation), Stephen Brown (University of Ottawa), David Gillies (The North-South Institute, Ottawa), Christian R. Hennemeyer (Bridging the Divide), Lisa Kammerud (International Foundation for Electoral Systems, Washington, DC), Johann Kriegler (Electoral Complaints Commission, Afghanistan and IFES Executive Advisory Council), Marc A. Lemieux (University of Ottawa), Khalid Mustafa Medani (McGill University), Susanne D. Mueller (Visiting Researcher at Boston University's African Studies Center), Ben Reilly (Australian National University and Johns Hopkins University's School of Advanced International Studies), Gerald J. Schmitz (M.A., University of Saskatchewan; PhD, Carleton University), Sara Staino (International IDEA), Vincent Tohbi (graduate, National Administration School, Abidjan, Ivory Coast), Francesc Vendrell (Princeton University), and Eugenia Zorbas (Canadian Department of Foreign Affairs and International Trade).  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConflict management. 0aDemocracy. 0aElections. 0aPolitical violence. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh1 aAxworthy, Thomas S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGillies, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHennemeyer, Christian R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKammerud, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKriegler, Johann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemieux, Marc A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMedani, Khalid Mustafa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMueller, Susanne D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReilly, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmitz, Gerald J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStaino, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTohbi, Vincent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVendrell, Francesc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZorbas, Eugenia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358574440uh